The truth, as usual, is more complicated. The four artists the Times profil=
ed were mostly market phenomenons, without much institutional support from =
museums and galleries. Some of them were selling directly from their studio=
s, often over Instagram, without the oversight of a single experienced deal=
er. (In one case, it would appear the artist was also consigning work to au=
ction directly from the studio.) In a couple of cases, the artists=E2=80=99=
 work was similar to other artists who had already had market success. And =
several of the artists were aggressively making work to satisfy demand, rat=
her than working through an idea=E2=80=94which leads to the creation of con=
sumer products, not art. Believe it or not, the market actually takes note =
of sincerity.

It=E2=80=99s perfectly understandable why some artists resent working with =
galleries, which often
take a significant cut of sales to cover their costs. But good galleries al=
so vet potential buyers and place the artist=E2=80=99s work with collectors=
 and institutions that will enhance their artists=E2=80=99 reputations over=
 time and increase the value of their work. They also reduce downside risk =
for artists by essentially policing the market to protect their clients fro=
m a collapse in prices during a downturn=E2=80=94which is likely what happe=
ned to Lewis, Taku, Ismail, and Zuckerman. If they had worked with gallerie=
s, their dealers could have kept collectors from selling on the open market=
 by offering to privately place that work for them, or else by threatening =
to take away access to the gallery=E2=80=99s other artists.

That=E2=80=99s not to say that speculators don=E2=80=99t exist. One of the =
artists profiled by the Times had also been discovered by a group of very a=
ctive market participants, who bought the artist=E2=80=99s work early with =
the intention of benefiting from the artist=E2=80=99s
market success. These market participants were indeed true speculators=E2=
=80=94they thought they saw value before others. But they were also the ear=
liest buyers, meaning the speculators preceded any collectors, essentially =
acting as angel investors for an artist who might not have had any patronag=
e otherwise. A lot is made of speculators in the art market, but without th=
em, many artists would never see any sales at all. It=E2=80=99s the specula=
tive money that supports many artists at the beginning of their careers. It=
=E2=80=99s also not without risk for the investors. Of course, if a young a=
rtist becomes spectacularly successful, their earliest buyers will benefit;=
 but if an artist doesn=E2=80=99t pan out, the speculator ends up owning=E2=
=80=A6 a lot of worthless art.

=E2=80=9CZombie=E2=80=9D Myths

But the most telling line in the Times story, which undercut its credibilit=
y, was this one: =E2=80=9CWhat happened to the bull market and the notion t=
hat all artworks appreciate in value?=E2=80=9D No one in the art world has =
ever believed that. Only a tiny fraction of artworks produced ever become v=
aluable, as everybody in this business knows. And if you don=E2=80=99t know=
 that, well, you probably shouldn=E2=80=99t be buying art.

The Times also presents several facts that are, at best, misleading. For ex=
ample, we=E2=80=99re told that in 2021, a third of the clients at Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s and Christie=E2=80=99s were new to the auction houses, and that =
these new buyers were all speculators. =E2=80=9CThey may have been more int=
erested in turning a profit than becoming lifelong patrons,=E2=80=9D the st=
ory says, paraphrasing another journalist=E2=80=99s opinion.

