0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">told the stories of<=
/a></u> four artists who saw their auction sales pop in the post-pandemic a=
rt boom, only to see their prices dramatically plummet over the last year a=
nd a half. None of this is surprising considering the fact that the <i>Time=
s</i> has always taken an ambivalent stance toward the art world. Its highl=
y educated and liberal-ish readership
cares about art and artists, but they are also easily put off by the idea t=
hat art is also a business. For some reason, the <i>Times</i> views the buy=
ing and selling of art with great suspicion and believes those who buy and =
sell art must be up to no good.  Much of the space in the <i>Times</i> prof=
ile is given over to the four artists complaining about what they considere=
d unfair treatment, mostly by offstage speculators. (One of the artists, <b=
>Amani</b> <b>Lewis</b>, went so far as to attack one of her collectors, wh=
o sold a work for pretty much what he had paid for it.) The problem wasn=E2=
=80=99t so much that the collector sold the work but that, in trying to sel=
l for significant profit, the collector had inadvertently revealed that the=
re was little demand for Lewis=E2=80=99s work at the moment. <br/><br/>The =
quartet of artists=E2=80=94Lewis, <b>Emmanuel Taku</b>, <b>Isshaq Ismail</b=
>, and <b>Allison Zuckerman</b>=E2=80=94each have a different story, but th=
e <i>Times</i> tried to flatten their
experiences into <i>one</i> story of exploitation. The real head-scratcher,=
 however, is how any of these artists expect to emerge from this blip in th=
eir careers unscathed. When demand for an artist evaporates, we usually see=
 no market activity at all. Over time, an artist can eventually make bad au=
ction results irrelevant. Complaining about your market going south in <i>T=
he</i> <i>New York Times</i> leaves a lasting record of an event best left =
unmentioned, and attacking your <i>collectors </i>is the sort of thing that=
=E2=80=99s harder to live down.  <br/></td>
