x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">But the most tellin=
g line in the <i>Times</i> story, which undercut its credibility, was this =
one: =E2=80=9CWhat happened to the bull market and the notion that all artw=
orks appreciate in value?=E2=80=9D No one in the art world has ever believe=
d that. Only a tiny fraction of artworks produced ever become valuable, as =
everybody in this business knows. And if <i>you</i> don=E2=80=99t know that=
, well, you probably shouldn=E2=80=99t be buying art. <br/><br/>The <i>Time=
s </i>also presents several facts that are, at best, misleading. For exampl=
e, we=E2=80=99re told that in 2021, a third of the clients at Sotheby=E2=80=
=99s and Christie=E2=80=99s were new to the auction houses, and that these =
new buyers were all speculators. =E2=80=9CThey may have been more intereste=
d in turning a profit than becoming lifelong patrons,=E2=80=9D the story sa=
ys, paraphrasing another journalist=E2=80=99s opinion.  <br/></td>
